bug.short_desc: Search CVS data corrupted

long_desc.thetext:
Not sure what happened, but it seems we got chocolate in our peanut butter, and peanut butter in our chocolate.
Seriously, though, if you check a query like http://www.eclipse.org/emf/searchcvs.php?q=file%3Aorg.eclipse.emf%2F+days%3A+7&project=0 you'll see things like files changed with commit comments/bugzilla #s that don't match, committers who don't have commit rights to a project supposedly changing files (like kmoir updating images in emf.doc), and viewcvs deltas that yield no changes.
And why does img004b.gif (http://dev.eclipse.org/viewcvs/indextools.cgi/~checkout~/org.eclipse.emf/doc/org.eclipse.emf.doc/tutorials/clibmod/images/Attic/img004b.gif) come up so many times when it's in the attic and it hasn't been changed in two years (http://dev.eclipse.org/viewcvs/indextools.cgi/~checkout~/org.eclipse.emf/doc/org.eclipse.emf.doc/tutorials/clibmod/images/Attic/img004b.gif?rev=1.2&content-type=text/vnd.viewcvs-markup) ?
Please investigate; if needs be, we can scuttle the database (now that those divide by zero errors are gone) and start anew.
Created an attachment (id=50623) screenshot

I've locally run through all of the projects that we're indexing now and everything appears to be fine. Clearing out the db on emft and repopulating it should do the trick, the parser likely threw in some incorrect data when it got confused.
Database wiped clean; reloading now.
<arms up in field goal gesture> It's good!

bug.short_desc: Race conditions in Query inner class of SiteSearchCategory

long_desc.thetext:
There are serious race problems with the inner Query class and more specifically with the use of the other inner class FeatureDownloader.
When a SiteSearchCategory is not constructed with liteFeaturesAreOk set to true and the update site is not extended, a pool of threads is used to start downloading the feature jars. Unfortunately this triggers a lot of callbacks in monitors, searchcollectors and filters, none of them guarded and all of them acessing unsynchronized collections. As none of them specify that they need to be guarded, these can even be in 'client' code.
I noticed this bug when writing my own commandline update client (I had some needs that required more then the StandaloneUpdateApplication). I based my code on the StandaloneUpdateApplication, and it has the same issue. When accessing the main eclipse site with both tools on a dual core system, over half of the times I got IllegalStateExceptions, ZipClosed exceptions etc. I was puzzled because the workbench wizard was working properly, however I noticed it was the only one who set the liteFeaturesAreOk boolean which triggers a synchronous single thread download.

More info : for liteFeaturesAreOk to have the intended effect and work arround the threads, the update site MUST declare a valid digest, wich I'm not sure many update sites do. As far as I can tell it's not very well documented (or perhaps I'm looking wrong).
So for instance http://update.eclipse.org/updates/site.xml is not ok, http://update.eclipse.org/updates/3.2/site.xml is.

Ok scratch part of the last remark : the 3.2 update site http://update.eclipse.org/updates/3.2/site.xml is not ok, as it lists digestURL="http://download.eclipse.org/updates/3.2/" and the update system goes looking for http://download.eclipse.org/updates/3.2/digest.zip while the file seems available from http://update.eclipse.org/updates/3.2/digest.zip.

The callisto site however is ok, so the work arround for this problem is to have - a proper digest on the site - make sure the code sets litefeatures
This does make me more concerned about the bug however. It means that any update site not listing a proper digest will experience race conditions when updated even with the update wizard. In time of hyperthreaded and dual core pc's this does sound grave.

bug.short_desc: Update API needs rework

long_desc.thetext:
Request for Enhancement: rework of the Update api in a full fledged, supported api. This bug might appear as a duplicate of the many small requests but maybe it can serve more as an umbrella bug.
I've lately been writing my own command line update client and it took me to the innards of the update systems which reveals a lot of it's faults and problems. Many people have been asking for several enhancements and some have voiced concern about why features are even needed in an OSGi runtime.
* The update api as it is is a pain to use, due to the lack of documentation. * The code is dodgy at some places, contains race conditions and internally uses a lot of deprecated eclipse code, bypassing the OSGi calls. It was orginally created as an experimental api during R2.0 and it's starting to show its age. * Using the api propely at times requires acessing internal classes which have discouraged access. This is most noticable if you want to implement dependecy tracking, like the 'select required' button in the install wizard does. * This in turn touches another difficult problem, most of the update/install logic is written inside the wizard panes, while things as dependency resolving and showing only the most recent features in a good api should be done by the update core itself as not to mess up the platform. This causes code duplication in other update clients and eventually they get out of sync (See the StandAloneUpdate). * The update wizard requires a live workbench but there are usecases for not having a workbench (small on itself standing application) * Error reporting is a real pain with code writing exceptions to system.out or the eclipse log directly, not passing decent error reporting back to the client code.
This bug is not ment to flame, simply to gather thoughts on how the api might be improved. With callisto, the update system has become a center stage player and I supspect it will become even more important over time.

bug.short_desc: Change ViewerSorter.getComparator?

long_desc.thetext:
20060920
We have an API class JavaElementSorter that extends ViewerSorter. I can't change that as it would be API breaking but I was hoping that that I could still be used as both a ViewerSorter and a ViewerComparator as ViewerSorter extends ViewerComparator .
Internally I changed our code to only use getComparator when comparing elements, to avoid any use of getCollator. The APi is still there, but just for API compability
Unfortunatly ViewerSorter reimplements getComparator and replaces it with getCollator. This blocks all accesses to the comparator instance in the ViewerComparator.
One possibility I see is:
Change ViewerSorter(Collator c) to call super(c), so no overriding of getComparator is required. In our case we would call ViewerSorter(null) and overwrite getComparator and getCollator to lazy create the collator (see other bug).

We implemented it the current way so that it was clear when you were using a ViewerSorter you would be using a java.text.Collator and when you used ViewerComparator it was clear you were using something other than java.text.Collator (well, in theory you could use the java Collator but why bother when ViewerSorter is available to use).
Boris, do we want to adopt this suggested implementation? The only problem I can see with it is it can become less clear which collator is being used when clients use a ViewerSorter.
I think it would be good to deprecate getCollator and field collator and suggest to use getComparator instead.

Created an attachment (id=50851) apply patch to org.eclipse.jface
Boris, here is a patch of the suggested solution - what do you think? This strategy would prevent having to create new comparator classes to replace the sorter classes that are currently API (see bug 157495).

The patch looks good to me, sorry that it took me so long to find a quiet moment to look at this.
That said, I would still prefer deprecating the existing subclasses of ViewerSorter and creating new ones that only inherit from ViewerComparator. (Assuming that this does not cause disproportional amounts of work for us and for clients.)
It does not seem a good practice to me to subclass ViewerSorter and then hope that everybody will just call getComparator() and never getCollator().

Duplicating the API classes will just double our maintenance as we end upm with 2 sorters that have to provide the same funtionality. I think keeping API classes that extend ViewerSorter is the best solution: just deprecate getCollator. Note that our JavaElementSorter is not intended to be extended by clients, so its only the code inside the JavaElementSorter that has to be changed (by us) to use getComparator. Ok, getCollator is even public, but there's not much reason to create a sorter and the call getCollator. -> deprecate getCollator and collator, but leave ViewerSorter non-deprecated so that our API subclasses stay clean.

Discussed with Boris and Tod. We will not deprecate ViewerSorter class to avoid potentially creating lots of warnings in subclasses and because lots of ViewerSorters may not even use a collator, but will deprecate the collator field and getter. The comment recommending use of ViewerComparator will remain in the class comment of ViewerSorter. And, of course, ViewerSorter#getComparator will be removed.
UI will likely deprecate their API subclasses of ViewerSorter and provide subclasses of ViewerComparator (see bug 147495).

bug.short_desc: Import of an exported openUP method plug-in fails

long_desc.thetext:
When I export the openUP mehtod plug-in (from latest library: OpenUP_library_20060914.zip) and try to import the plug-in in another library, I get the following eror message: "IUPE0205E: The specified files were exported by a previous version of Eclipse Process Framework Composer. You must export files using the current version of Eclipse Process Framework Composer."
However, I used the same version (latest one: 1.0-RC2-N20060920-1805) for both - the export and import.

This is as desgined. The lib has not got the epf tool version number on it. The tool is backward compatible, and allows loading of a lib created by previous tool. The tool would change the version number in the libray file only if something gets modified. Otherwise, the version number would not change and the import would correctly reject such a library.
We should update the epf tool version number in OpenUp.

Addtional notes:
For CM consideration, epf tool does not touch the library files unless something gets modified.
Export/import does not support backward compatibility.

There is actually some inconsistency among different types of exports with respect to tool version number update. Regular plugin export is the only type that does simple file copy without calling the tool's persistency layer to export the file. Therefore, the version number would not get updated in the exported file. Not updating the version number is correct in this case, as the underlying exported library files are still old. I think, the correct apporach to solve this user issue is to update the version number of OpenUp.
Work-around is to add a new plugin and then delete it before exporting plugins. This would cause the current tool version number added to library.xmi.
Still can recreate on build RC2 0924, comment #4 can avoid this bug.
v,closed.

bug.short_desc: [common] Improve reporting of CoreException(MultiStatus)

long_desc.thetext: CoreException is in the o.e.equinox.common bundle.

The CoreException.printStackTrace() prints the status object's trace only if the getException() of the status object is not null. In your example is it is null.
Also, for MultiStatus, the MultiStatus itself has to have an exception associated with it for the CoreException.printStackTrace() to produce an output.

(In reply to comment #2) That's an explanation of the current behavior, but it doesn't solve the problem.
If CoreException is incapable of printing all information of the given MultiStatus, then this should be documented in CoreException. Core/Resources would then have to reimplement their error handling to not use a MultiStatus in a CoreException any more. However, I still think this should be fixed in CoreException.

I agree that this is a problematic situation, but it seems to be approached from the wrong end.
It doesn't look like CoreException is intended to do any special processing for MultiStatus. It takes an IStatus object (which just happens to be a MultiStatus in this particular case).
The CoreExeption class is not trying to consolidate MultiStatus - and I don't think it should as all it knows about is an IStatus.
In terms of the state of things today, if MultiStatus is used to construct a CoreExeption object, the MultiStatus shold contain meaningful status message and, if appropriate, originating exception. The CoreExeption itself doesn't do any processing of the status message.
Could this be improved? Probably. However, this needs to be improved in the error reporting first with, probably, a couple of new methods on the MultiStatus / Status / IStatus.
If you'd like, let's reopen this as an enhancement request with a slightly different title - something like "Improve reporting of the CoreException(MultiStatus)".

> The CoreExeption class is not trying to consolidate MultiStatus - and I don't > think it should as all it knows about is an IStatus. IStatus already contains the protocol of MultiStatus (except for mutators), so I don't think it's too far-fetched to handle nested statuses as well.
> If you'd like, let's reopen this as an enhancement request with a slightly > different title - something like "Improve reporting of the > CoreException(MultiStatus)". Done, thanks.

The issue here is that the BookmarkView has a key listener installed for the delete key, which runs the delete bookmark action. Then the command handler for delete gets executed, which causes the delete action to run again. Since the marker is deleted the first time, and the viewer is not yet updated, the second delete request tries to delete the same marker, which by this time no longer exists.
I can code around the NPE in AbstractMarkersOperation, but doing so will cause a different error dialog informing the user that the marker cannot be deleted because it no longer exists.
The question is why there is a delete key handler in the view vs. relying on the command mechanism. Having both is a problem. This problem may have been around for awhile, with the second delete quietly failing, but now that the undo code is used, there is stricter error checking and information given the user, since undo commands can go stale.
Tod and/or Paul - any thoughts? I can code the remove bookmark action to check for non-existent markers and ignore them completely before creating the undo operation, but the right thing to do seems to be to avoid the duplication.
We should just use the command - the key listener is legacy code.

bug.short_desc: Add possibility to share working sets

long_desc.thetext:
Hi,
I have a couple of suggestion related two team work and version controll
1. team/project working set
When working in teams, I have often found a need for a way to share working sets.
When working with version controlled software, you might be working on several versions of the project at the same time. Typically implementing new features in one version and correcting TRs in older versions.
As it is now, one has to define the same working set for each version of the project you open. Some working sets may be common to all team members. For example you want to have a working set for the source code you want to run PMD static code checks on.
If adding the pssobility to define project specific working sets, which are saved with the other project files and can be put under version controll, it would ease the work a lot. Those working sets would only be valid for the files in the current project. If opening another version of the working set, it would automatically point out the same files for that project.
2. Variable part of Project Names
The project name in the .project file could have a variable part.
As it is now you have to modify the project name for each version if you want to open two versions at once. This seems unnecessary. If a variable part could be added, like ClearCase view name, version number of the file or anything that would automatically distinguish the two versions, it would be great!
Best Regards,
Daniel Persson
Move to Platform/Team

As of 3.3 M1, The Team Project Set export allows you to include working sets. The exported project set can be placed in a shared file. This facility may meet your needs. Of it doesn;t, feel free to log enhancement requests (i.e. I know you're asking for more than that heere but it is not clear from your description exactly what you mean. You may want to describe yur scenario in more detail if you htink it is not solved by the project set export).

Hi,
As I understand it, the support in 3.3M1 is only for CVS. What I am thinking of would be a more general thing. I am working with ClearCase but what I am thinking of should not depend on which SCM you are using.
I will try to clarify what I am thinking of a little more.
Suppose you are working with a product, call it ProductA. Product A has bee nreleased to the market in revision R1 and R2. Design organisation is currently working with next revision, R3. At the same time they are correcting Trouble Reports in R1 and R2.
The branchin strategy used is to create a new branch in the SCM system on modified files for each corrected TR and for each work package implemented in the development release, R3.
Designers want to have multiple versions of the project open in Eclipse at the same time. For example one R3 project for implementing new features and one or two TR correction projects for correcting TRs in revision R1 and R2 of the product.
In order to do that, fo each new project to open in Eclipse, the designer change the name of the project to for example ProductA_R2_TR123. Otherwise Eclipse will not be able to open multiple versions at the same time.
This leads to that Working Sets will have to be redefined all the time for each new TR-correction branch done.
Even if multiple users open the same product version they would each have to define the same working sets.
The ProductA has requirements to run some Plugin builders to do static code analysis. As a major part of the code is generated code, it should be excluded when running such checks. Therefore Working Sets are defined to include only the code that should be checked.
So one can see that it is a repetitive step that should be able to automate.
In order to automate these steps there are some different solutions.
Analoguos to how Run & Debug launch files can be share and put as part of the project in the SCM system, Working Sets should also be possible to have a project files and store them in the SCM together with the .project file etc.
This would then be a good start. Multiple designers could reuse the same working set as someone else already defined.
But there is one more step that would add to usability. As the designers change the name of the project for each version opened, the working sets will only be valid for the project they were defined in.
So by making a shared working set relative to the current project, instead of having it statically fixed to a certain project, then reuse of working sets for various revisions of the same Project would be made easier.
This could be done by either allowing to associate a working set with several projects, or by allowing to have a variable part of the definition of the project path in the working set definition, so that one can have that variable point to current project to make it dynamic.
This last part would also be usable to have for shared launch configurations.
FInally, the last thing that could be useful would be if one would not have to change the name of the project for each version of the product one want to have open in Eclipse at the same time.
This could of course be harder to get information for, but having a variable part that could be read from some special file or in some way making it possible automatically give each version of the Product a unique project name.
To conclude, here is the suggestions in short:
1 - Making it possible to share working sets and save them together with other project files in the SCM so that they can be reused by multiple users and in multiple versions of the product/project. THis should be independent of SCM system used. Analoguous to Launch files is a suggestion.
2 - Making Working Sets relative to current project instead of fixed to only one project. If they are stored together with a project, then the working sets would automatically point out the project if multiple versions of the product/project are opened in parallell.
3 - Introduce a variable part of project names in the .project file. This would allow to automatically give different versions of the same product/project a unique name and thus make it possible to open different versions in parallell without manual steps.
I hope this description makes it a little bit clearer.
Best Regards,
Daniel Persson

Regarding your suggestions:
1) The project set import is not CVS specific so an export of a project set can include projects from any repository provider and, optionally, any working sets.
2) Working sets are provided by Platform/UI. You should log an enhancement request against that component. IF you want the ability to export working sets on their own, you should also request that from Platform/UI.
3) This is covered by bug 77637.
I'm marking this as WONTFIX since we, the Team component, do not plan on addressing the issue. You could reopen it and assign it to Platform/UI but I woudl suggest that you will have more of a chance of getting this fixed if you log a separate enhancement for each of the pieces you desire (i.e. one for working set export and one for project relative working sets).

bug.short_desc: Windows Event Log rules adapters may generate incorrect creationTime values

long_desc.thetext:
https://cs.opensource.ibm.com/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=10654
Steps to Reproduce: 1. Import a WAS activity log (text version) with the rules-based adapter. 2. Notice that some of the creationTime values do not match the timestamps in the corresponding records in the log file.
This problem was introduced in AC 4.2 when the substitution rule for creation time was changed to use the @TIMEZONE and timeFormat string options.
TPTP adapter to be modified 1. Windows Security 2. Windows Application 3. Windows System
As per discussion with Uliyana and Eric canging the severity to critical

While there is a problem parsing some log files with a rules adapter that uses a timeFormat string to parse a timestamp that includes fractional seconds, it does not affect the Windows Event log adapters. This is because the Windows Event logs do not include a fractional second value but the EventLogReader program that converts the binary event log into a text file pads the timestamp with a fractional second value of 6 zeros (eg. CreationTime: 10/24/2005 14:25:05.000000;). The fractional seconds are only an issue if they are non-zero. In the Windows Event log case I believe they will always be zero. I have never encountered one where it was non zero. Therefore, I will downgrade the severity to normal since the problem has never been encountered with Windows Event Logs. However, I'll target this to 4.3 to fix the creationTime rule to truncate the fractional seconds to 3 digits in case the event logs change in the future to generate timestamps with longer fractional seconds. This downgrading has been negotiated with Eric Labadie who represents the consuming product who opened this bugzilla.
Deferring to 4.4 as it is not a stop ship issue and cannot be contained in 4.3.
Added sizing.
Targetting to fix in i3 and increasing priority to indicate it is planned for 4.4.
Changing to a more appropriate component. The adapter files are in the Monitor.Analysis component.

Committed fix to TPTP Head CVS.
The fix was to change the match pattern in the creationTime rule from
"(\d{2}/\d{2}/\d{4}\s\d{2}:\d{2}:\d{2}\.\d{6})"
to
"(\d{2}/\d{2}/\d{4}\s\d{2}:\d{2}:\d{2}\.\d{3})\d{3}"
in all Windows event log adapter files.

bug.short_desc: [server] consider a mechanism to get resources from the backing container

long_desc.thetext: ServletContextAdaptor does not delegate calls like getResource to the underlying container, and we should probably have an option to support this.

Early on the servletbridge provided resource access to the underlying container for "getResources" and "getResourcesStream". This ended up causing problems in mixed webapp environments for some users where property and config files were inadvertently read from the underlying container. I think that at least by default we don't want to provide access.
If we did want to provide access, the ServletContext is 1-to-1 tied to the HttpContext, so one way to support access might be to set some identifier on the HttpContext and then use Reflection to find it. This might be overkill and a real pain to use.
Perhaps a better way might be to use a "special" init-param when initializing the HttpServiceServlet to designate the subsequent HttpService as providing access to the underlying container.
I'd suggest we "wait and see" a concrete use-case before acting here as there might be better ways to provide access.
I'm downgrading this to an enhancement and barring a good use-case don't plan to add this for 3.3.
We can re-open this if there's a good use-case

The plugin org.eclipse.wst.common.modulecore reduced it's version number from 1.1.2 to 1.1.1 in last week's 1.5.1 I-build. This type of change this late in the cycle can be disruptive and breaks any adopter product that has added plugin version require statements based on 1.5.1.
I assume that 1.1.2 was a mistake that was being fixed, but opening this bug to confirm that (in case changing it was a mistake) and to make sure you are aware that this was a breaking change.
It was updated it looks like on accident to 1.1.2 on 8/29 and was reverted back on 9/13, so it should not be an issue.
Closing.
This is part of a "mass update" where bugs showing "fixed" between 7/1/2006 and 9/27/2006 are assumed fixed in WTP 1.5.1. feel free to change the target milestone if you know a more accurate setting.

The servlet.bridge bundles have already been re-named once so I'm not keen on the idea of renaming them again. Also, "servlet-bridge" is a name that is sometimes used to describe this stuff so I'd like to keep it.

This has been fixed.

bug.short_desc: [server] generate the extension bundle on startup

long_desc.thetext: Because the extension bundle is speicfic to each container it could be generated on startup of the servletbridge.jar.

I've added support for generating the servletbridge's extension bundle at runtime on the HEAD. In particular, exporting the correct version of the Servlet API has been confusing and this change will simplify configuration. By default the Servlet API and o.e.e.servletbridge are exported. Additional exports may be added by using the "extendedFrameworkExport" ServletConfig init-param in web.xml.

bug.short_desc: [server] Design a filtering mechanism to decide against which service instance a servlet is registered

long_desc.thetext: The current implementation of http.registry registers all servlete and resources against all the sercies available. We need a way to filter that. Two solutions: 1) an ldap filter in the xml, but this will limit the reusability of the bundle 2) getting the values from the config admin service

As an initial step I like your first suggestion; adding an LDAP service registration filter to the xml. It's fairly straight-forward and handles the use-case although admittedly at a cost in terms of reusability. By default if no filter is specified all servlets, resources, and httpcontexts will continue to be associated with all services.
I'd like to track the runtime config approach in a separate bug as it's more involved and I'm less sure on the timing.

I can't help but feel this is a bad direction. It violates the producer/consumer separation and encourages "bad" behaviour. Config admin is one way. Something akin to the capabilities mechanism where a third party describes the set of contributions that should be linked into a particular server is another (similar) approach.
My hesitation here is that we will introduce something that basically we will then tell people to not use.

Alright. I'll buy that we should wait on this as there isn't really a pressing need at the moment as its quite rare to run more than one HttpService in a single VM.
I understand the producer/consumer concern and it's definitely legitimate. I'm relatively comfortable with a "filter" attribute however as I think that eventually we could use it at runtime. I'm hoping we can dynamically alter an extension and then receive and respond to a "changed" event. We don't have this capability currently so I'll accept that we shouldn't tie ourselves to the static approach. [Untargetting until we have a more concrete approach.]
I think that the recent plugin "customization" worked talk about on the dev list is relevant to this bug report. ...offering to help test here.

I disagree. This mechanism should not be used as an excuse for sloppy design, or part of a solution for customizability. This xml processing mechanism should be used for backward compatibility issues and "bad plugins" in the context of a product. Therefore I would not expect the eclipse platform to ship with such files or recommend its usage.
Also there are no guarantee that this mechanism will make it into eclipse

I agree that the customization should only be used to deal with problem situations.
The approach we're considering is to add a <serviceSelector/> element (to the servlets and resources extensions) that will have two modes of operation. The first takes an ldap "filter" as an attribute and uses it to filter which Http Service to register agains. The second approach uses a "class" attribute that will cause instantiation of a Filter class capable of arbitrary filtering -- one example being to create a filter from Config Admin.
To try and address re-usability we're adding the capability to define your extensions in a separate plugin from your resources. See bug 163586

bug.short_desc: [server] Need a factory to create http server on various ports

long_desc.thetext: With the current implementation of the jetty bridge, it is not possible to create multiple servers on different ports.
You might want to consider doing this with OSGi's Managed Service Factory specification, which allows configurations to be created using Configuration Admin. In my experience it works pretty well.
That's the plan... Of course we'd better look at graduating the config admin implementation first.

It would be worth considering how users of the server will be expected to configure a registered Managed Service Factory, and potentially a Managed Service. bug.short_desc: Request a warning value for osgi.resolverMode

long_desc.thetext: Currently, osgi.resolverMode has a value of strict which effectively removes the bundle exports with the attribute x-internal:=true; What the WebSphere team would like is an additional value of something like warning that cause a warning message to get logged when accessing an export with the x-internal:=true attribute. When in the warning mode, allow access to the classes exported with the x-internal:=true, but, generate the warning. This will allow us to do analysis of which internal classes (which have the export attribute of x-internal:=true) are being accessed in an application prior to enforcing the strict mode. Another suggestion is that we need a way to see which code segment is accessing classes with the x-internal:=true. Perhaps a call stack dump along with the warning message.

A new resolver mode may not be the proper place to specify this. The resolver mode only takes affect at resolve time, not class load time.
Would adding an new trace option work for you. You would enable this by adding a new option to a .options file and launching with -debug .options to enable the tracing. Something like:
org.eclipse.osgi/debug/loader/internalaccess=true

Personaly I'm against bloating the framework with such an option. What is being asked does not resort to the framework, but rather to bundle tooling such as PDE or the API checker tool under investigation.

This request is against the runtime framework and not the tooling because not all of the code that access our internal classes can or will use the PDE or API tool checker tool.
We like the idea of the debug like option. The one problem is that we would be programmically setting this option. If possible, having it as a command line option is better than a debug option. With the debug option approach, we have some difficult scenarios, do we have a predefined .options file with the entry and then what if we need to have customer set other debug options. It can get messy to code. With a command line option separate from the debug options we have a way to set this mode programatically without affecting the ability for other debugging.

If addig the debug option is dead simple then it seems like a good approach. If it requires new classes or whatever to distinguish differnet kinds of imports then this will impact the caching code etc and is less attractive.
As for tooling, API analysis tools can be run on any JAR or class file. The tooling should catch most cases but will of course miss reflect calls etc.
Note that people are also free to implement a classloading hook that could do the warning.
investigate a debug option for 3.3 M7. If it is dead simple to implement we can consider it for 3.3.

bug.short_desc: indexing failures due to MSVC extensions

long_desc.thetext:
A blocker for Win32 development is silent failures while parsing due to unrecognized compiler extensions. Win32 SDKs, even when building with Cygwin, will have sources with the MSVC extension "__declspec( <stuff> )", primarily to mark symbols for import or export. Without this support, SDK classes, each of whose methods are imported/exported, are instead full of IProblemNodes, which obviously limits the success of a search.
__declspec() has functionally equivalent extensions as GCC's __attribute__() but it appears in the declarator part of a declaration rather than being tacked on to the end. GCC supports __declspec under Cygwin as well.
I tested a solution by implementing parser support similarly to __attribute__ (i.e., adding a configuration flag to the parser extension configuration, then if allowed, parsing it and throwing everything away). A more complete solution would have both the existing __attribute__ parsing and __declspec parsing add declaration specifiers to the DOM, since they contain information that may be useful in the future (for instance, marking API as deprecated, which can aid code completion).
Is this is an appropriate solution?
